Dear CSA Community,
>>>>>>> master
CSA District Parent Council’s 23rd Annual Beluga Ball is also our first virtual Beluga Ball… and you’re invited! Please go to https://belugaball.cbo.io to preview our auction.
Our Silent Auction will open for bidding on Monday, June 15th and close on Saturday, June 20th at 7:00pm.
As our Silent Auction closes, our Live Auction portion of our premier virtual Beluga Ball will begin on Saturday, June 20th beginning at 7:00pm.
You must register at https://belugaball.cbo.io to bid on any Silent or Live Auction items. Please invite your family, friends and neighbors to visit our auction site, too. Everyone is welcome to register to “attend” our very first virtual Beluga Ball!
We look forward to “seeing” you all in the LiveStream on Saturday, June 20th!
-Liam Barlow, Deb Curcuru, Mary Harvey, and Tara Urbaniak
Beluga Ball 2020 Co-chairs

post_text: After reading Even Superheroes Make Mistakes, Narwhals were inspired to challenge themselves to a domino stacking game using a growth mindset! This book inspired the Narwhals to keep encouraging each other, even when a mistake is made. The Narwhals worked as a team and encouraged one another through this stacking challenge to see how many dominoes they could stack into a tower. When a domino fell down, Narwhals made sure to spread encouraging and kind words to one another to keep the challenge going!
text: After reading Even Superheroes Make Mistakes, Narwhals were inspired to challenge themselves to a domino stacking game using a growth mindset! This book inspired the Narwhals to keep encouraging each other, even when a mistake is made. The Narwhals worked as a team and encouraged one another through this stacking challenge to see how many dominoes they could stack into a tower. When a domino fell down, Narwhals made sure to spread encouraging and kind words to one another to keep the challenge going!

post_text: During our Math-In Day, Narwhals spent some time learning how to play Math Pentathlon games. A new Narwhal favorite is Kings & Quads. Narwhals used their critical thinking skills to strategically place different chips and game pieces throughout their board to make their "King's" way to their opponent' s side or trap their opponent's "King" using their chips so they can no longer move around the board.

post_text: After researching and learning about Aurora Borealis, Narwhals took an interest in creating their own Aurora Borealis projects. Using rips of scrap paper, oil pastels, and sidewalk chalk, Narwhals put their creativity to the test to design a scene that included the phenomenon of bright, colorful lights in the night sky. Narwhals were amazed by the science behind these amazing lights and awestruck by the mystical lights.

post_text: Orca's last science unit was on forces and interactions, which meant there were lots of hands-on experiments! Here is a picture of a group of students working together to first balance a scale and then using the balanced scale to find out how many washers are equal to one of the weights! They definitely had to work hard and work together to discover the answer!

post_text: A little spot of kindness! Beluga students read a book titled “A Little Spot of Kindness” which covered all the different ways each of us can show and spread kindness. They enjoyed listening to the story, sharing our ideas, and making their own little spot of kindness character. Throughout the year they have two jars in the classroom called, the kindness jar and acts of kindness jar. Students who witness kindness in the classroom/school will take once puff ball from the kindness jar and place it into the acts of kindness jar. When the acts of kindness jar is full the students will have a rich discussion of the types of kindness witnessed or acted upon in the classroom.

post_text: The Risso Class had a special guest, Risso Teacher of the day, to help teach a special lesson from what seemed to be an ordinary rock. They passed around a rough bumpy stone and noticed how it looked and felt. They learned that they could break open the plain dusty stone and see dazzling beautiful crystal's on the inside. This special type of rock, called a geode, reminded them that 'it's what's on the inside that counts.' They tied the theme of 'beauty within' to the six character traits (respect, kindness, getting along, optimism, work ethic and responsibility). They learned that each one of them has their own 'character crystals' deep inside and its through their actions, words and thoughts that they let their crystals show.

video_thumbnail: After reading Even Superheroes Make Mistakes, Narwhals were inspired to challenge themselves to a domino stacking game using a growth mindset! This book inspired the Narwhals to keep encouraging each other, even when a mistake is made. The Narwhals worked as a team and encouraged one another through this stacking challenge to see how many dominoes they could stack into a tower. When a domino fell down, Narwhals made sure to spread encouraging and kind words to one another to keep the challenge going!

post_text: During our Math-In Day, Narwhals spent some time learning how to play Math Pentathlon games. A new Narwhal favorite is Kings & Quads. Narwhals used their critical thinking skills to strategically place different chips and game pieces throughout their board to make their "King's" way to their opponent' s side or trap their opponent's "King" using their chips so they can no longer move around the board.

post_text: After researching and learning about Aurora Borealis, Narwhals took an interest in creating their own Aurora Borealis projects. Using rips of scrap paper, oil pastels, and sidewalk chalk, Narwhals put their creativity to the test to design a scene that included the phenomenon of bright, colorful lights in the night sky. Narwhals were amazed by the science behind these amazing lights and awestruck by the mystical lights.

Each student received one puzzle piece and starting with all the edges pieces and then working our way in we all used positive and encouraging word until it was complete! post_text: Baiji students have studied Native Americans, New World Explorers and the first Colonists. The people of the past were not able to go to the store and simply purchase needed items. They would barter and trade amongst each other or travel to trading posts. Explorer students created homemade items and took part in the "Trade Fair!" Explorers had the opportunity to experience firsthand how different cultures obtained goods they needed for survival!

They would barter and trade amongst each other or travel to trading posts. Explorer students created homemade items and took part in the "Trade Fair!" Explorers had the opportunity to experience firsthand how different cultures obtained goods they needed for survival!

post_text: The Risso class celebrated the New Year with a "Noon Year" celebration. They made hats, and counted down til the stroke of noon. They also talked about goal setting as the class wrote New Year's resolutions for 2020. The practice of consistent reflection and goal setting is a huge part of the CSA way for students, teachers and our community. They also talked about trying to set goals that were helpful/beneficial to themselves, their family and/or the world.

post_text: March is an exciting time at CSA! It’s National Reading Month where we celebrate the joy of reading and writing. During the next weeks, we have many new and exciting activities planned to enhance, encourage and re-ignite students’ love for literacy including classrooms doors decorated to showcase different genres and authors, buddy reading across units, special performances by the Wild Swan Theater, Skyping with authors and so much more! Also, be sure to check out our Facebook Page to watch one of your favorite CSA teachers or staff members share a favorite read aloud each day. Happy Reading!

post_text: What a day for our CSA district as our Middle and High School students participated in our 4th Annual Hike for Heat!!! This event really showcases our dedication to nurturing the Whole Child. Our students are practicing Kindness and Care during an event that is designed to benefit others. They are hiking with friends and connecting socially. Finally, they are walking between 4 to 6 miles in the falling snow, a true physical/sensory experience! Thanks to all who participated in some way:)

post_text: We're thrilled to give you a sneak peek of the exciting transformation occurring at the site of the new Charyl Stockwell Academy Middle School. Today we'll have media and school officials gathered to share renderings and details about the building transformation. And since YOU are our inspiration for these changes, we wanted you to be able to be a part of the action. You can tune in LIVE here on our Facebook page at 1:30 p.m. today. Thank you for being a part of The CSA Way. We can't wait for what's next!

post_text: On Friday, Beluga students kicked off a new unit of study by conducting an experiment. Before starting the experiment students discussed what scientist do; they pose a question (I wonder…), form a hypothesis (I think…), conduct the experiment (I see…), record observations (I Discovered…), and come to a conclusion (I Know…) Next, students talked about ice and shared their ideas when answering the question, what is ice and what melts ice? Finally, students conducted the experiment to see if air, water, sugar or salt melts ice the fastest!
